al, Westmorland, England":"Rydal, Westmorland, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Grasmere, Westmorland, England":"Grasmere, Westmorland, England"},"en":{"1460–1562":"1460–1562","1455–1532":"1455–1532","1475–1558":"1475–1558","1480–Female":"1480–Deceased","1484–Female":"1484–Deceased","1485–Female":"1485–Deceased","1490–Female":"1490–Deceased","1497–1557":"1497–1557","about 1480":"about 1480","1484":"1484","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1558":"1558","1557":"1557","1532":"1532","1455":"1455","1497":"1497","1475":"1475","1485":"1485","1562":"1562","about 1475":"about 1475","about 1484":"about 1484","5 October 1558":"5 October 1558","Westmorland, England, United Kingdom":"Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Lowther, Westmorland, England":"Lowther, Westmorland, England","Grayrigg, Westmorland, England":"Grayrigg, Westmorland, England","Rydal, Westmorland, England":"Rydal, Westmorland, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Grasmere, Westmorland, England":"Grasmere, Westmorland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lowther","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Cumbria, so called from the river on which it stands. The placename is of obscure etymology, perhaps of ancient Welsh origin (compare   Lauder  ), or from Old Norse <i>lauthr</i> ‘froth, foam’ + <i>á</i> ‘river’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lawther","meanings":["Scottish, northern Irish, and northern English: variant of   Lowther   and   Lauder  ."]},{"name":"Lauder","meanings":["Scottish (Borders): habitational name from Lauder in Berwickshire, originally a name for the river Leader (itself from British <i>lou-</i> + <i>dubro-</i> ‘cleansing river’). Compare   Lauderdale  ."]},{"name":"Lattea","meanings":["Altered form of English   Lowther  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Lowther was born in 1460, in Westmorland, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son and 5 daughters with Sir John Flemming. She died in 1562, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 102."},"et":{"1460–1562":"1460–1562","1455–1532":"1455–1532","1475–1558":"1475–1558","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1484–Female":"1484–Surnud","1485–Female":"1485–Surnud","1490–Female":"1490–Surnud","1497–1557":"1497–1557","about 1480":"umbes 1480","1484":"1484","1460":"1460","1480":